'''Alejandro "Alex" Zendejas Saavedra''' (born February 7, 1998) is a professional [[Association football|soccer]] player who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Liga MX]] side [[Club América]]. Born in Mexico, he represents the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States national team]].

==Early life==
Zendejas was born in [[Ciudad Juárez]] in [[Mexico]] before moving to the [[United States]] at a young age.

The [[Major League Soccer|MLS]], [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]], and [[FC Dallas]] websites all listed him as being born in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]], [[Texas]], but FC Dallas later confirmed that Zendejas had been born in Mexico.<ref name="twitter.com" />

==Club career==
===FC Dallas===
On October 1, 2014, Zendejas signed a [[Homegrown Player Rule (Major League Soccer)|homegrown]] player contract with [[FC Dallas]], making him the 13th homegrown signing in club history. However, he was not eligible to play for the first team until the 2015 season.<ref>{{cite web|title=FC Dallas signs 13th Homegrown player Alejandro Zendejas|url=http://www.fcdallas.com/news/2014/10/fc-dallas-signs-13th-homegrown-player-alejandro-zendejas|website=FCDallas.com|publisher=FC Dallas Media Services|accessdate=May 2, 2015|date=October 1, 2014|archive-date=September 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924012617/http://www.fcdallas.com/news/2014/10/fc-dallas-signs-13th-homegrown-player-alejandro-zendejas|url-status=dead}}</ref> Zendejas made his professional debut on 1 May 2015, in a 4–1 victory over [[Houston Dynamo]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lovell|first1=Darrell|title=Match Recap: FC Dallas 4, Houston Dynamo 1|url=http://www.fcdallas.com/news/2015/05/match-recap-fc-dallas-4-houston-dynamo-1|website=FCDallas.com|accessdate=May 2, 2015|date=May 1, 2015|archive-date=September 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924013004/http://www.fcdallas.com/news/2015/05/match-recap-fc-dallas-4-houston-dynamo-1|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Guadalajara===
====2016–17: Debut season, Copa MX title, and first league title====
On June 23, 2016, Zendejas signed with Liga MX [[C.D. Guadalajara|Guadalajara]]. In order to meet with the club's tradition of only using Mexican players,<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.chivasdecorazon.com.mx/noticias/27157/nueva-incorporacin-para-el-rebao|title=Nueva incorporación para el Rebaño|last=C.V.|first=Chivas de Corazon S.A. de|date=March 15, 2024 |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/story/2900883/fc-dallas-winger-alex-zendejas-set-to-join-chivas-sources|title=FC Dallas winger Alex Zendejas set to join Chivas - sources|publisher=}}</ref> Zendejas agreed to reject future U.S. national team call-ups and accept Mexico national team call-ups if they ever occur.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|title=Sources: FC Dallas homegrown Zendejas set for Chivas move|url=http://www.goal.com/en-us/news/69/transfer-zone/2016/06/23/24977342/source-fc-dallas-homegrown-zendejas-set-for-chivas-move|website=goal.com|publisher=Ives Galarcep and Jon Arnold|accessdate=June 23, 2016|date=June 23, 2016}}</ref> Zendejas was registered with the first team and was given the number 29 jersey, the same kit he had at Dallas. Zendejas made his [[Liga MX]] debut on August 6, in a match against [[Querétaro F.C.|Querétaro]].<ref name="auto2">{{cite web|url=http://www.ligamx.net/cancha/jugador/117446/alejandro-zendejas-saavedra|title=LIGA MX - Página Oficial de la Liga del Fútbol Profesional en México .: Bienvenido|first=LIGA MX / ASCENSO|last=MX|website=www.ligamx.net}}</ref>

====2017–18: Loan to Zacatepec====
In a press conference, Chivas coach [[Matías Almeyda]] confirmed some youth players would be sent out on loan to sister club [[Atlético Zacatepec|Zacatepec]] to get playing time. On 8 June 2017, Zacatepec announced they had signed Zendejas on loan. Zendejas scored his first professional goal in a [[Copa MX]] match against [[Cruz Azul]]. He scored his first [[Ascenso MX]] goal on August 12, 2017, against [[Murciélagos F.C.]] Zacatepec would go on to win 1–0 with his goal.<ref name="auto2"/>

===Necaxa===
On June 29, 2020, Zendejas joined [[Club Necaxa]] on a free transfer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/futbol/liga-mx/necaxa-alejandro-zendejas-deja-chivas-viste-rayo|title = Necaxa. Alejandro Zendejas deja a Chivas y se viste de Rayo| date=June 25, 2020 }}</ref>

===América===
On January 17, 2022, Zendejas joined [[Club América|América]] for $3 million.

==International career==
===United States U15 and U17===
Zendejas was a member the [[United States men's national under-17 soccer team|United States under-17]] squad that competed at the [[2015 CONCACAF U-17 Championship]] playing alongside future USMNT stars [[Christian Pulisic]] and [[Tyler Adams]]. Overall, he gained 27 caps and scored four goals for the U-17 national team.<ref>{{cite web|title=2015 statistics|url=http://www.ussoccer.com/us-under17-mens-national-team/stats|website=USsoccer.com|accessdate=May 2, 2015}}</ref> After joining Mexican club [[C.D. Guadalajara]], Zendejas agreed to reject future U.S. national team call-ups and accept Mexico national team call-ups if they occur.

===Mexico===
In August 2017, Zendejas was called up to the [[Mexico national under-21 football team|Mexico under-21]] squad for games in [[China]] and [[Qatar]], the start of preparation for the [[Summer Olympic Games|Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]] in [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/columnistas-luis-castillo/sorpresas-en-sub-21|title=Sorpresas en Sub 21|last=a.esteban|date=August 25, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

Zendejas received his first call-up to the [[Mexico national football team|national team]] by [[Gerardo Martino]], and made his debut on 27 October 2021 in a friendly match against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]], coming in as a substitute in the 65th minute for [[Uriel Antuna]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.espn.com.mx/futbol/selecciones/nota/_/id/9419048/alejandro-zendejas-convocado-tri-seleccion-mexicana-historia|title= Alejandro Zendejas, el nuevo jugador del Tri que rompe el molde del futbolista mexicano|website=espn.com.mx|date=October 25, 2021}}</ref>

===National team controversy===
In late August 2022, [[FIFA]] issued an investigation probe on the [[Mexican Football Federation]] regarding Zendejas' call-ups to friendly matches in October 2021 and April 2022, against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] and [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] respectively, the matches themselves were non-FIFA regulated matches but nevertheless, Zendejas' national team allegiance was still under the 'legal' jurisdiction of the [[United States Soccer Federation]], meaning that Zendejas had taken part in friendly matches for Mexico without consulting or filing a [[FIFA eligibility rules|one-time switch]] to FIFA in order to [[List of association footballers who have been capped for two senior national teams|switch]] national team allegiances, a violation of FIFA regulations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/soccer/news/alejandro-zendejas-mexico-case-fifa-to-investigate-ex-usmnt-prospects-dual-national-eligibility-per-reports/amp/|title=Alejandro Zendejas-Mexico case: FIFA to investigate ex-USMNT prospect's dual national eligibility, per reports|date=26 August 2022|work=CBS Soccer |first=Chuck|last=Booth}}</ref>

On November 9, 2022, Zendejas’ attorneys revealed to media that the player was considering representing the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/es-es/deportes/futbol/alejandro-zendejas-se-decanta-por-la-selección-de-estados-unidos-sobre-la-selección-mexicana/ar-AA140faY|title=Alejandro Zendejas se decanta por la selección de Estados Unidos sobre la selección mexicana|language=es|website=MSN.com|date=11 November 2022}}</ref>

On January 19, 2023, FIFA ordered [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] to forfeit two friendlies—a 3–2 loss against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] on October 28, 2021, and a 0–0 draw with [[Guatemala national football team|Guatemala]] on April 22, 2022— and pay a 10,000 [[Swiss Franc]] fine for using Zendejas in violation of regulations. The [[Mexico national under-23 football team|Mexico under-23 team]] was also ordered to forfeit three games in which Zendejas played.<ref>{{cite web |title=FIFA orders Mexico to forfeit Zendejas matches |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4855790/mexico-forfeits-matchesfined-by-fifa-over-usmnts-alejandro-zendejas |website=ESPN.com |access-date=19 January 2023 |language=en |date=19 January 2023}}</ref>

===United States===
On January 17, 2023, Zendejas was included in the list of United States national team call ups for two friendlies against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]] and [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]], as he had never applied to FIFA for a one-time switch in affiliation to be allowed to appear for the Mexico national team.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hernandez |first1=Cesar |title=Sources: U.S. calls 2 dual nationals to Jan. camp |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/united-states-usa/story/4854723/usa-calls-dual-nationals-vazquezzendejas-for-january-camp |website=ESPN.com |access-date=19 January 2023 |language=en |date=18 January 2023}}</ref>

In January 2023, Zendejas became the fifth player to earn caps for both national teams in the history of the [[Mexico–United States soccer rivalry|Mexico–U.S.]] football rivalry and only the second Mexican-born to do so since [[Martín Vásquez]].

On March 14, 2023, [[United States Soccer Federation|U.S. Soccer]] announced that Zendejas had officially committed to play internationally for the United States on a permanent basis.<ref>{{Cite web|first=Paul|last=Tenorio|title=Alex Zendejas commits to USMNT after switching from Mexico's team|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4308314/2023/03/14/alex-zendejas-usmnt-commitment-roster/|date=2023-03-14 |website=[[The Athletic]]|language=en}}</ref>

